{"title_page": "Eusebio Serna", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Eusebio Serna\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Spanish\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|6|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Eusebio Serna''' (born 13 June 1961) is a Spanish [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed in the [[Wrestling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 74 kg|men's freestyle 74 kg]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/eusebio-serna-1.html |title=Eusebio Serna Olympic Results |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serna, Eusebio}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Spain-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Eusebio Serna\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Spanish\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|6|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Eusebio Serna''' (born 13 June 1961) is a Spanish [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed in the [[Wrestling at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 74 kg|men's freestyle 74 kg]] at the [[1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/eusebio-serna-1.html |title=Eusebio Serna Olympic Results |accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serna, Eusebio}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1988 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Spain-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eusebio_Serna"}
{"title_page": "Setbacks (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Setbacks\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[ScHoolboy Q]]\n| cover      = SCHOOLBOYQSETBACKS.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 11, 2011\n| recorded   = 2010<br />TDE Recording Studio: House of Pain<br /><small>([[Carson, California]])</small>\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[West Coast hip hop]], [[experimental hip hop]]\n| length     = 62:36\n| label      = [[Top Dawg Entertainment]]\n| producer   = Lord Quest, [[Willie B (producer)|Willie B]], [[Focus...]], Phonix Beats, Dae One, [[Tae Beast]], DJ Wes, King Blue, [[Rahki]], [[Tommy_Black_(producer)|Tommy Black]], [[Sounwave]]\n| prev_title = Gangsta & Soul\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = [[Habits & Contradictions]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n}}\n\n'''''Setbacks''''' is the debut [[studio album]] by [[United States|American]] [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] recording artist [[ScHoolboy Q]], released for [[Music download|digital download]] on January 11, 2011 under Top Dawg Entertainment. The album features [[guest appearance]]s from his fellow [[Black Hippy]] members [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Jay Rock]] and [[Ab-Soul]], as well as vocals from [[singer-songwriter]]s Alori Joh, [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]] and [[BJ the Chicago Kid]]. The album's [[Hip hop production|production]] was handled by Lord Quest, Willie B, [[Focus...]], [[Rahki]], Phonix Beats, [[Tae Beast]], DJ Wes, King Blue, [[Sounwave]] and more.\n\nSchoolboy Q titled the album ''Setbacks'', due to the limitations he experienced and endured before releasing the album. After the release of ''Setbacks'', the album reached number 100 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], number 12 on the [[Top Rap Albums]], number 25 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and number 13 on the [[Top Independent Albums]] chart. Only a few weeks after ''Setbacks'' was released, it already had 4,395 units and was praised by fans and critics alike.\n\n== Background ==\nIn 2012, in an interview with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', Schoolboy Q spoke on the concept behind ''Setbacks'': \"The concept behind ''Setbacks'' was [to talk about] all the shit that\u2019s the reason why I can\u2019t rap. The reason I can\u2019t accomplish what I want to accomplish is because I\u2019m doing all this dumb shit. I put it all together on the album. Like, \u2018Druggys Wit Hoes,\u2019 I'm out here drugging and I'm not even trying to fuck with hoes. \u2018Kamikaze,\u2019 I'm not even trying to rap\u2014keep going broke. Different shit like that, I sum it up all in one album. My life did a whole 180 after that dropped. A lot of people still didn't know the name though, but a lot of people did. It was weird. It just took me to the right spot. I made some fucking money off the project, it helped me see that I needed to do more positive shit in life, and it made me into the person I am now. All I do now is just chill. I'd rather just chill, work on my music, be with my two-year-old daughter, and smoke weed and shit.\"<ref name=\"complex7\">{{cite web|author=Insanu Ahmed|title=Who Is Schoolboy Q? - His previous independent album, Setbacks|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/02/who-is-schoolboy-q#8|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=February 3, 2012|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> Two weeks after the album's release ScHoolboy Q released it for free via his [[Twitter]] feed. The free version doesn't include \"LigHt Years AHead\" and is replaced with \"Live Again\" which also features Kendrick Lamar. The free version also features a new bonus track titled \"Fuck Ya Hip Hop\" featuring [[Big Pooh]] and [[Murs (rapper)|Murs]]<ref>[http://dctobc.com/2011/01/schoolboy-q-setbacks-album/ ScHoolboy Q Setbacks Album Free Version] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014130250/http://dctobc.com/2011/01/schoolboy-q-setbacks-album/ |date=2011-10-14 }}, DCtoBC.com</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Commercial performance ===\nThe album debuted at number 100 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and had sold 17,000 copies in the US as of February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5915807/schoolboy-q-heading-for-no-1-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|title=ScHoolboy Q Heading for No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|last=Ramirez|first=Rauly|date=February 26, 2014|accessdate=February 26, 2014|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''Setbacks'' received generally positive reviews from music critics, who praised the album's production, features and lyrics. iHipHop gave it a 3.5 out of 5 rating mentioning \"While ''Setbacks'' is a misleading title, ScHoolboy Q does leave room for critique. Despite his overwhelmingly impressive flow, Q rarely says anything worthy of raising an eyebrow.\"<ref>[http://www.ihiphop.com/?p=79358 Album Review: ScHoolboy Q - Setbacks] iHipHop.com</ref> [[Allmusic]] gave it 4 out of 5 stars commenting \"Dividing his time between socially conscious rap and bud smoker\u2019s anthems, ScHoolboy Q makes quite the impression on his debut \u201cstreet album\u201d\". They called ''Setbacks'' polished, funky, well-balanced, and rewarding.<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/setbacks-r2133100 Setbacks - ScHoolboy Q] Allmusic.com</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track list\n| total_length    = 62:36\n| extra_column = Producer\n| title1 = Figg Get Da Money\n| extra1 = LordQuest\n| length1 = 3:59\n\n| title2 = Kamikaze\n| extra2 = [[Willie B (producer)|Willie B]] of [[Digi+Phonics]]\n| length2 = 4:03\n\n| title3 = LigHt Years Ahead (Sky High)\n| note3 = featuring [[Kendrick Lamar]]\n| extra3 = [[Focus...]]\n| length3 = 4:11\n\n| title4 = WHat's THa Word\n| note4 = featuring [[Jay Rock]]\n| extra4 = Phonix Beats\n| length4 = 3:51\n\n| title5 = #BETIGOTSUMWEED\n| extra5 = [[Tae Beast]] of Digi+Phonics\n| length5 = 4:55\n\n| title6 = Druggys Wit Hoes\n| note6 = featuring [[Ab-Soul]]\n| extra6 = Tae Beast of Digi+Phonics\n| length6 = 3:50\n\n| title7 = Cycle\n| extra7 = DJ Wes\n| length7 = 4:09\n\n| title8 = To THa Beat (F'd Up)\n| extra8 = King Blue of Sore Losers\n| length8 = 3:47\n\n| title9 = Crazy\n| extra9 = [[Sounwave]] of Digi+Phonics\n| length9 = 3:06\n\n| title10 = PHenomenon\n| note10 = featuring Alori Joh \n| extra10 = Phonix Beats\n| length10 = 5:01\n\n| title11 = Situations\n| extra11 = [[Rahki]]\n| length11 = 4:24\n\n| title12 = Fantasy\n| note12 = featuring [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]]\n| extra12 = [[Tommy_Black_(producer)|Tommy Black]]\n| length12 = 4:27\n\n| title13 = I'm Good\n| note13 = featuring [[BJ the Chicago Kid]] & [[Punch (rapper)|Punch]]\n| extra13 = Tae Beast of Digi+Phonics\n| length13 = 4:57\n\n| title14 = Birds & The Beez\n| extra14 = [[DAE ONE]]\n| note14 = featuring Kendrick Lamar\n| length14 = 4:20\n\n| title15 = Rolling Stone\n| extra15 = Sounwave of Digi+Phonics\n| note15 = [[Black Hippy]]) ([[Bonus track]]\n| length15 = 3:36\n}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2011)<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/setbacks-r2133100/charts-awards]</ref>\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|100\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Top Rap Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Independent Albums|Top Independent Albums]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Schoolboy Q}}\n\n[[Category:2011 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Schoolboy Q albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Sounwave]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Focus...]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Tae Beast]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Willie B]]\n[[Category:Top Dawg Entertainment albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Setbacks\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[ScHoolboy Q]]\n| cover      = SCHOOLBOYQSETBACKS.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 11, 2011\n| recorded   = 2010<br />TDE Recording Studio: House of Pain<br /><small>([[Carson, California]])</small>\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]], [[West Coast hip hop]], [[experimental hip hop]]\n| length     = 62:36\n| label      = [[Top Dawg Entertainment]]\n| producer   = Lord Quest, [[Willie B (producer)|Willie B]], [[Focus...]], Phonix Beats, Dae One, [[Tae Beast]], DJ Wes, King Blue, [[Rahki]], [[Tommy_Black_(producer)|Tommy Black]], [[Sounwave]]\n| prev_title = Gangsta & Soul\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = [[Habits & Contradictions]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n}}\n\n'''''Setbacks''''' is the debut [[studio album]] by [[United States|American]] [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] recording artist [[ScHoolboy Q]], released for [[Music download|digital download]] on January 11, 2011 under Top Dawg Entertainment. The album features [[guest appearance]]s from his fellow [[Black Hippy]] members [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Jay Rock]] and [[Ab-Soul]], as well as vocals from [[singer-songwriter]]s Alori Joh, [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]] and [[BJ the Chicago Kid]]. The album's [[Hip hop production|production]] was handled by Lord Quest, Willie B, [[Focus...]], [[Rahki]], Phonix Beats, [[Tae Beast]], DJ Wes, King Blue, [[Sounwave]] and more.\n\nSchoolboy Q titled the album ''Setbacks'', due to the limitations he experienced and endured before releasing the album. After the release of ''Setbacks'', the album reached number 100 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], number 12 on the [[Top Rap Albums]], number 25 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and number 13 on the [[Top Independent Albums]] chart. Only a few weeks after ''Setbacks'' was released, it already had 4,395 units and was praised by fans and critics alike.\n\n== Background ==\nIn 2012, in an interview with ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', Schoolboy Q spoke on the concept behind ''Setbacks'': \"The concept behind ''Setbacks'' was [to talk about] all the shit that\u2019s the reason why I can\u2019t rap. The reason I can\u2019t accomplish what I want to accomplish is because I\u2019m doing all this dumb shit. I put it all together on the album. Like, \u2018Druggys Wit Hoes,\u2019 I\u2019m out here drugging and I\u2019m not even trying to fuck with hoes. \u2018Kamikaze,\u2019 I\u2019m not even trying to rap\u2014keep going broke. Different shit like that, I sum it up all in one album. My life did a whole 180 after that dropped. A lot of people still didn\u2019t know the name though, but a lot of people did. It was weird. It just took me to the right spot. I made some fucking money off the project, it helped me see that I needed to do more positive shit in life, and it made me into the person I am now. All I do now is just chill. I\u2019d rather just chill, work on my music, be with my two-year-old daughter, and smoke weed and shit.\"<ref name=\"complex7\">{{cite web|author=Insanu Ahmed|title=Who Is Schoolboy Q? - His previous independent album, Setbacks|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/02/who-is-schoolboy-q#8|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=February 3, 2012|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> Two weeks after the album's release ScHoolboy Q released it for free via his [[Twitter]] feed. The free version doesn't include \"LigHt Years AHead\" and is replaced with \"Live Again\" which also features Kendrick Lamar. The free version also features a new bonus track titled \"Fuck Ya Hip Hop\" featuring [[Big Pooh]] and [[Murs (rapper)|Murs]]<ref>[http://dctobc.com/2011/01/schoolboy-q-setbacks-album/ ScHoolboy Q Setbacks Album Free Version] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014130250/http://dctobc.com/2011/01/schoolboy-q-setbacks-album/ |date=2011-10-14 }}, DCtoBC.com</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Commercial performance ===\nThe album debuted at number 100 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and had sold 17,000 copies in the US as of February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5915807/schoolboy-q-heading-for-no-1-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|title=ScHoolboy Q Heading for No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|last=Ramirez|first=Rauly|date=February 26, 2014|accessdate=February 26, 2014|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''Setbacks'' received generally positive reviews from music critics, who praised the album's production, features and lyrics. iHipHop gave it a 3.5 out of 5 rating mentioning \"While ''Setbacks'' is a misleading title, ScHoolboy Q does leave room for critique. Despite his overwhelmingly impressive flow, Q rarely says anything worthy of raising an eyebrow.\"<ref>[http://www.ihiphop.com/?p=79358 Album Review: ScHoolboy Q - Setbacks] iHipHop.com</ref> [[Allmusic]] gave it 4 out of 5 stars commenting \"Dividing his time between socially conscious rap and bud smoker\u2019s anthems, ScHoolboy Q makes quite the impression on his debut \u201cstreet album\u201d\". They called ''Setbacks'' polished, funky, well-balanced, and rewarding.<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/setbacks-r2133100 Setbacks - ScHoolboy Q] Allmusic.com</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track list\n| total_length    = 62:36\n| extra_column = Producer\n| title1 = Figg Get Da Money\n| extra1 = LordQuest\n| length1 = 3:59\n\n| title2 = Kamikaze\n| extra2 = [[Willie B (producer)|Willie B]] of [[Digi+Phonics]]\n| length2 = 4:03\n\n| title3 = LigHt Years Ahead (Sky High)\n| note3 = featuring [[Kendrick Lamar]]\n| extra3 = [[Focus...]]\n| length3 = 4:11\n\n| title4 = WHat's THa Word\n| note4 = featuring [[Jay Rock]]\n| extra4 = Phonix Beats\n| length4 = 3:51\n\n| title5 = #BETIGOTSUMWEED\n| extra5 = [[Tae Beast]] of Digi+Phonics\n| length5 = 4:55\n\n| title6 = Druggys Wit Hoes\n| note6 = featuring [[Ab-Soul]]\n| extra6 = Tae Beast of Digi+Phonics\n| length6 = 3:50\n\n| title7 = Cycle\n| extra7 = DJ Wes\n| length7 = 4:09\n\n| title8 = To THa Beat (F'd Up)\n| extra8 = King Blue o